Headline: Data Scientist | Machine Learning | Data Visualization
About:
I'm a Data Science student at Barnard College, Columbia University, minoring in Middle Eastern and South Asian studies. I am interested in intersections the of data science and social good, machine learning and public policy, as well as how to develop ethical AI. As a Muslim woman of color, and first-generation college student, I'm passionate about using data to make a meaningful impact in my community.

My coursework has equipped me with a solid foundation in data-related subjects, databases, and machine learning, from Data Structures, Analysis in Algorithms, Applied Machine Learning, Statistical Inference, to Introduction to Databases. My experience and coursework has deepened my understanding of analysis-end ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) processes by covering data modeling, normalization, and SQL for data manipulation. This foundation enabled me to develop efficient ETL workflows that prepare and transform data for analytical purposes, ensuring data integrity and optimizing performance for large-scale data collections, as well as preparing data for future machine learning pipelines. 

My technical skills encompass Python, R, Java/Javascript, Git, Linux, Excel, QGIS, and SQL, along with proficiency in machine learning frameworks like Pandas, Matplotlib, NumPy, Scikit-Learn, and more. 

I've gained practical experience at Break Through Tech, Coding it Forward, and Barnard Empirical Reasoning Center, contributing to real-world data projects utilizing machine learning, data analysis and data visualization tactics to tackle issues such as gender inequality in the workplace, automating health grant categorization, and gentrification and policing. 

My research experience includes co-authoring a paper presented at the Fifth Widening NLP workshop at the 2021 Empirical Methods for Natural Language Processing Conference. This research involved scraping and analyzing Reddit posts using the Pushshift API to investigate changes in narratives of pregnancy before and after COVID-19 using natural language processing and machine learning methods.

As a Teaching Assistant at Columbia Justice Through Code, I helped formerly incarcerated individuals learn essential tech skills. Additionally, I'm a peer tutor at the Barnard Empirical Reasoning Center. These roles have provided me with a breadth of experience in distilling complex computer science material into accessible language for non-technical audiences. 

I've demonstrated leadership as the President of the Columbia Muslim Student Association E-Board, fostering a sense of community.

Headline: Machine Learning Engineer at Meta
About:
During my graduate research in astrophysics I uncovered the first evidence of a free-floating planet while mining a dataset of gravitational microlensing events. Later, I became fascinated with a formidable modeling problem needed to better understand blackhole accretion disks. This required building and efficiently scaling a distributed simulation that performs random lookups spanning a large supercomputer cluster. My Ph.D. advisor discouraged me from working on it fearing that it was too difficult. Despite the challenges and his doubts, I persisted and solved it. This experience taught me that the computer science and data science aspects of my research were more interesting to me than science of astrophysics.

Next, I re-entered the tech industry with a mixture of consulting for clients, leading an applied research team, and exploring a variety of side projects while at Gravity Jack. Machine learning became my focus. This included organizing a meet up to help inspire and educate others in ML and deep learning.
